00:16:46,560 --> 00:16:50,840
Bill, this is Ms. Sims from
the district attorney's office.

268
00:16:50,840 --> 00:16:52,324
- [Bill] Ms. Sims.

269
00:16:52,324 --> 00:16:53,250
- [Sue] And of course Detective Ortega.

270
00:16:53,250 --> 00:16:54,083
- [Bill] Detective.

271
00:16:54,083 --> 00:16:55,672
- [Ortega] Mr. Dillard.

272
00:16:55,672 --> 00:16:56,505
- [Bill] Please, sit down.

273
00:16:59,210 --> 00:17:02,393
This is my son Bill Junior
and his wife Mary Helen.

274
00:17:07,150 --> 00:17:09,450
- I'm so sorry for your loss.

275
00:17:09,450 --> 00:17:11,404
I promise you, we'll do everything we can

276
00:17:11,404 --> 00:17:13,534
to get to the bottom of this.

277
00:17:13,534 --> 00:17:15,640
- Now I have seen the toxicology report

278
00:17:15,640 --> 00:17:19,713
from the autopsy, and it
was definitely arsenic.

279
00:17:20,806 --> 00:17:21,730
- I just don't understand who

280
00:17:21,730 --> 00:17:25,049
would want to poison our
Nancy, I really don't.

281
00:17:25,049 --> 00:17:27,050
Who would do such a thing?

282
00:17:27,050 --> 00:17:29,440
- Oh Mama, I'll tell you who,

283
00:17:29,440 --> 00:17:31,373
Richard, her husband, that's who.

284
00:17:31,373 --> 00:17:35,051
- Yes I understand that you
have reason to suspect Mr. Lyon.

285
00:17:35,051 --> 00:17:38,819
- He gave her poisoned
pills, poisoned wine,

286
00:17:38,819 --> 00:17:40,580
she dies of poison.

287
00:17:40,580 --> 00:17:43,072
- Well the wine checked out clean,

288
00:17:43,072 --> 00:17:47,120
the pills contained the
poison barium carbonate,

289
00:17:47,120 --> 00:17:51,170
that is not that effective
on humans, it's for rats.

290
00:17:51,170 --> 00:17:52,710
- I can understand your anger.

291
00:17:52,710 --> 00:17:54,940
But if Mr. Lyon did poison his wife,

292
00:17:54,940 --> 00:17:56,750
we still have to make a case.

293
00:17:56,750 --> 00:18:00,646
- And why would Mr. Lyon
want to poison Mrs. Lyon?

294
00:18:00,646 --> 00:18:03,990
- For the money, why else.?

295
00:18:03,990 --> 00:18:05,474
- Oh perhaps.

296
00:18:05,474 --> 00:18:09,321
Richard left our Nancy for
another woman not long ago.

297
00:18:09,321 --> 00:18:13,293
It didn't work out I suppose,
she was younger than him.

298
00:18:14,240 --> 00:18:16,370
- Who was this other woman?

299
00:18:16,370 --> 00:18:18,130
- Bridgette Tyler.

300
00:18:18,130 --> 00:18:19,323
- What happened, happened.

301
00:18:20,339 --> 00:18:22,210
Richard and Nancy reconciled,

302
00:18:22,210 --> 00:18:24,677
they were trying to put
their marriage back together,

303
00:18:24,677 --> 00:18:27,560
at least we'd hoped so.

304
00:18:27,560 --> 00:18:31,810
- Soon after that her health
goes south, now she's dead.

305
00:18:31,810 --> 00:18:34,840
He's there in the hose
with the girls, who's next?

306
00:18:34,840 --> 00:18:36,695
- Oh honey calm down, let
the detective do his job.

307
00:18:36,695 --> 00:18:39,764
- Now do you have any
ideas about the arsenic,

308
00:18:39,764 --> 00:18:42,796
where it might have come from,

309
00:18:42,796 --> 00:18:46,521
did Nancy use arsenic for anything?

310
00:18:46,521 --> 00:18:49,400
- No, not that I know of.

311
00:18:49,400 --> 00:18:51,300
- I can't imagine what for.

312
00:18:51,300 --> 00:18:53,020
- But you know shortly
after she and Richard

313
00:18:53,020 --> 00:18:54,950
got separated, when things got really bad,

314
00:18:54,950 --> 00:18:56,680
you remember Nancy told us that she found

315
00:18:56,680 --> 00:18:58,860
a check, I mean a carbon of a check,

316
00:18:58,860 --> 00:19:00,860
you know that Richard had
written to some company.

317
00:19:00,860 --> 00:19:03,020
She suspected that he was
buying all these drugs.

318
00:19:03,020 --> 00:19:04,743
She was afraid he was trying
to poison her back then.

319
00:19:04,743 --> 00:19:07,253
- Well did she tell you
the name of the company?

320
00:19:09,450 --> 00:19:11,520
- Oh I don't remember but
I think it was in Houston.

321
00:19:11,520 --> 00:19:14,723
But you know another time,
Richard had given her a soda

322
00:19:14,723 --> 00:19:17,290
that tasted strange to her, and she saw

323
00:19:17,290 --> 00:19:21,300
some kind of powder floating
on it, so she dumped it.

324
00:19:21,300 --> 00:19:22,322
- When was this?

325
00:19:22,322 --> 00:19:24,670
Nobody did anything?

326
00:19:24,670 --> 00:19:27,650
- Nancy was embarrassed,
she thought people

327
00:19:27,650 --> 00:19:29,980
would only think she was crazy.

328
00:19:29,980 --> 00:19:33,936
That it would sound like
the typical divorce story.

329
00:19:33,936 --> 00:19:36,123
It did seem a bit far fetched.

330
00:19:36,123 --> 00:19:37,214
- Can you think of anyone else

331
00:19:37,214 --> 00:19:39,973
who might have wanted to harm Nancy?

332
00:19:43,080 --> 00:19:44,453
- Everyone loved Nancy.

333
00:19:47,400 --> 00:19:52,400
- Well, if there's anything
else that you can think of,

334
00:19:53,570 --> 00:19:55,753
please, give us a call.

335
00:19:56,860 --> 00:19:58,953
- You mean you're not
gonna arrest Richard?

336
00:19:59,950 --> 00:20:01,750
- No, not 'til I have more evidence.

337
00:20:04,430 --> 00:20:05,802
Mr. Dillard.

338
00:20:05,802 --> 00:20:07,657
- Let me show you out.

339
00:20:14,844 --> 00:20:18,863
- I don't get it, she
suspects she's being poisoned

340
00:20:18,863 --> 00:20:21,980
but she doesn't do anything
about it, until it's too late.

341
00:20:21,980 --> 00:20:23,973
- Well nobody likes to
believe those things.

342
00:20:25,480 --> 00:20:27,888
(dog barking)

343
00:20:27,888 --> 00:20:30,638
(dramatic music)

344
00:20:47,419 --> 00:20:49,395
- Can Mommy see what I'm wearing?

345
00:20:49,395 --> 00:20:50,700
(dramatic music)

346
00:20:50,700 --> 00:20:52,174
- I think your mommy can see everything.

347
00:20:52,174 --> 00:20:55,900
- Anna says Mommy was in
the statue in the garden.

348
00:20:55,900 --> 00:20:57,712
- I saw the pretty flowers Anna.

349
00:20:57,712 --> 00:21:00,462
(dramatic music)

350
00:21:03,010 --> 00:21:04,563
It's gonna be okay sweetie.

351
00:21:04,563 --> 00:21:06,500
(dramatic music)

352
00:21:06,500 --> 00:21:08,358
It's all gonna be all right.

353
00:21:08,358 --> 00:21:11,108
(dramatic music)

354
00:21:14,500 --> 00:21:17,615
- Tell me not, the lower numbers,

355
00:21:17,615 --> 00:21:19,963
life is but an empty dream.

356
00:21:21,371 --> 00:21:24,188
For the soul is dead, it slumbers,

357
00:21:24,188 --> 00:21:27,453
things are not what they seem.

358
00:21:28,735 --> 00:21:33,513
Life is real, life is earnest,

359
00:21:34,720 --> 00:21:36,220
and the grave is not its goal.

360
00:21:37,969 --> 00:21:40,810
Dust thy are to dust returneth
is not spoken of the soul.

361
00:21:44,460 --> 00:21:49,460
Not enjoyment and not sorrow
is our destined end or way.

362
00:21:50,800 --> 00:21:55,800
But to act that each tomorrow
finds us farther than today.

363
00:21:58,030 --> 00:22:00,613
(solemn music)

364
00:22:04,050 --> 00:22:08,231
- Mrs. Chandler, do you
know anything about these

365
00:22:08,231 --> 00:22:12,970
vitamin pills that Mrs. Lyon
was supposed to be taking?

366
00:22:12,970 --> 00:22:14,410
- [Mrs. Chandler] Not really.

367
00:22:14,410 --> 00:22:17,200
- Did Mrs. Lyon mention her suspicions

368
00:22:17,200 --> 00:22:19,130
that Richard was trying to drug her?

369
00:22:19,130 --> 00:22:20,560
- Excuse me?

370
00:22:20,560 --> 00:22:22,110
- [Jerri] Anything about drugs.

371
00:22:23,197 --> 00:22:27,490
- Well I know that Nancy and
Richard were having problems,

372
00:22:27,490 --> 00:22:30,433
but I can't imagine Richard
giving drugs to anyone.

373
00:22:31,990 --> 00:22:33,990
- You knew that marriage
better than anybody,

374
00:22:33,990 --> 00:22:35,930
can you tell us about it?

375
00:22:35,930 --> 00:22:36,930
What was Nancy like?

376
00:22:38,208 --> 00:22:42,370
- Well, she was one of
those unprofessional mothers

377
00:22:42,370 --> 00:22:45,313
that you read about, always working hard.

378
00:22:46,914 --> 00:22:50,340
I mean she was very good at her job,

379
00:22:50,340 --> 00:22:52,968
I just look at all of her buildings.

380
00:22:52,968 --> 00:22:55,450
(phone ringing)

381
00:22:55,450 --> 00:22:58,029
I mean I was glad that she was busy,

382
00:22:58,029 --> 00:23:01,424
I loved those little girls.

383
00:23:01,424 --> 00:23:05,283
- And Richard, what about him?

384
00:23:07,334 --> 00:23:12,334
- Well Richard was, he
used to love to go into

385
00:23:13,030 --> 00:23:17,900
the garden with the
girls and plant flowers

386
00:23:17,900 --> 00:23:19,283
or some other project.

387
00:23:20,690 --> 00:23:22,613
And even when Nancy was there,

388
00:23:23,980 --> 00:23:26,374
lots of times she had work to do.

389
00:23:26,374 --> 00:23:29,124
(dramatic music)

390
00:23:30,829 --> 00:23:31,982
- [Richard] That's it.

391
00:23:31,982 --> 00:23:33,237
- [Allison] There.

392
00:23:33,237 --> 00:23:34,070
- [Richard] There we go.

393
00:23:34,070 --> 00:23:34,903
Okay sweetheart thank you.

394
00:23:34,903 --> 00:23:35,736
I'm gonna work in the fertilizer

395
00:23:35,736 --> 00:23:36,569
and you go over there and get the hose.

396
00:23:36,569 --> 00:23:38,735
- Fertilizer, that's
all he ever thinks of.

397
00:23:38,735 --> 00:23:40,167
- [Richard] I heard that.

398
00:23:40,167 --> 00:23:44,147
- Good, time to clean up.

399
00:23:44,147 --> 00:23:46,897
(dramatic music)

400
00:23:48,535 --> 00:23:50,002
Come on, party's in a few hours.

401
00:23:50,002 --> 00:23:51,535
(dramatic music)

402
00:23:51,535 --> 00:23:52,930
(water spraying)

403
00:23:52,930 --> 00:23:54,257
Allison, Allison.

404
00:23:54,257 --> 00:23:55,921
(Richard screaming)
(Allison laughing)

405
00:23:55,921 --> 00:23:58,216
- [Nancy] No, no, don't get that.

406
00:23:58,216 --> 00:23:59,540
- Oh you didn't.

407
00:23:59,540 --> 00:24:00,817
(Richard laughing)
(Allison screaming)

408
00:24:00,817 --> 00:24:02,270
(everyone laughing)

409
00:24:02,270 --> 00:24:04,474
You've got your own defense.

410
00:24:04,474 --> 00:24:05,602
- [Nancy] Oh yeah.

411
00:24:05,602 --> 00:24:06,988
(everyone laughing)

412
00:24:06,988 --> 00:24:09,910
- [Richard] Come on, come
on, I give up, I give up!

413
00:24:09,910 --> 00:24:11,493
Aha, I got you now.

414
00:24:12,435 --> 00:24:15,314
(everyone laughing)
(Nancy screaming)

415
00:24:15,314 --> 00:24:17,932
- Oh stop it, oh look at
what you did, look at this.

416
00:24:17,932 --> 00:24:18,888
Oh look what you did!

417
00:24:18,888 --> 00:24:20,816
- [Richard] Oh I'm sorry.

418
00:24:20,816 --> 00:24:21,649
- Look what you did.
- I'm sorry Nancy, really.

419
00:24:21,649 --> 00:24:22,902
- Look at this, it's all my work.

420
00:24:22,902 --> 00:24:24,462
You just ruined it.

421
00:24:24,462 --> 00:24:25,731
- I'm sorry.

422
00:24:25,731 --> 00:24:28,481
(dramatic music)

423
00:24:32,240 --> 00:24:33,360
- [Mrs. Chandler] I could see the pressure

424
00:24:33,360 --> 00:24:35,240
that Richard was under.

425
00:24:35,240 --> 00:24:36,464
Nancy was just more successful,

426
00:24:36,464 --> 00:24:39,513
and I think that made it hard for him.

427
00:24:40,876 --> 00:24:43,693
And then there were the family affairs.

428
00:24:44,710 --> 00:24:48,650
Richard, he always seemed so uncomfortable

429
00:24:48,650 --> 00:24:51,268
and I think he really tried.

430
00:24:51,268 --> 00:24:53,963
But he was an outsider.

431
00:24:55,150 --> 00:24:57,011
He just didn't fit in.

432
00:24:57,011 --> 00:25:02,011
(soft piano music)
(party goers chattering)

433
00:25:09,909 --> 00:25:13,760
(Bill and kids laughing)

434
00:25:13,760 --> 00:25:15,260
- They went that-a-way.

435
00:25:15,260 --> 00:25:16,881
Make sure they don't break anything.

436
00:25:16,881 --> 00:25:18,910
- They should be in the nursery,

437
00:25:18,910 --> 00:25:21,720
I never allowed you all to
run rampant through a party.

438
00:25:21,720 --> 00:25:24,428
- Mother, they're fine.

439
00:25:24,428 --> 00:25:27,345
(soft piano music)

440
00:25:31,295 --> 00:25:36,295
(party goers laughing)
(soft piano music)

441
00:25:37,131 --> 00:25:42,131
(Bill laughing)
(soft piano music)

442
00:25:52,714 --> 00:25:55,290
- To my daughter Nancy,
may her success continues.

443
00:25:55,290 --> 00:25:57,100
- [Everyone] To Nancy!

444
00:25:57,100 --> 00:26:00,840
- To my lovely, lovely sister Nancy.

445
00:26:00,840 --> 00:26:04,050
The finest architect the
Armadillo State has ever produced.

446
00:26:04,050 --> 00:26:04,883
- [Everyone] Here, here.

447
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:09,226
- Too bad she had to run
off and marry a damn Yankee.

448
00:26:09,226 --> 00:26:11,796
(Bill laughing)

449
00:26:11,796 --> 00:26:15,213
(party goers chattering)

450
00:26:19,740 --> 00:26:21,840
- [Richard] Why'd you have
to go off and marry a Yankee?

451
00:26:21,840 --> 00:26:24,870
- Oh, he's just kidding.

452
00:26:24,870 --> 00:26:28,030
Don't make such a big deal
our of every little thing.

453
00:26:28,030 --> 00:26:30,349
He had too much to drink.

454
00:26:30,349 --> 00:26:33,050
- He had more then too much
to drink and you know it.

455
00:26:33,050 --> 00:26:35,660
Or was that another Dillard family taboo

456
00:26:35,660 --> 00:26:36,830
we're not supposed to talk about.

457
00:26:36,830 --> 00:26:38,999
Everybody is perfect,
everybody is from Texas.

458
00:26:38,999 --> 00:26:41,343
- Richard, stop it.

459
00:26:41,343 --> 00:26:42,860
- I don't know how you deal with it,

460
00:26:42,860 --> 00:26:44,180
but I'll tell you something right now,

461
00:26:44,180 --> 00:26:46,027
I can't deal with it.

462
00:26:49,003 --> 00:26:50,953
- I guess that was part of the problem.

463
00:26:53,188 --> 00:26:55,123
I don't think Richard felt as successful

464
00:26:55,123 --> 00:26:57,163
as other people around him.

465
00:26:58,260 --> 00:27:00,603
He wasn't a Dillard, he never would be.

466
00:27:01,963 --> 00:27:03,977
- Is there anything else?

467
00:27:03,977 --> 00:27:07,350
- Well they did take a vacation

468
00:27:07,350 --> 00:27:11,146
or a trip of some kind, everybody.

469
00:27:11,146 --> 00:27:13,810
They went to Arizona
and when they came back,

470
00:27:13,810 --> 00:27:15,820
it's almost like they
were different people.

471
00:27:15,820 --> 00:27:17,211
- What do you mean?

472
00:27:17,211 --> 00:27:20,830
- Well Richard seemed
to be away all the time,

473
00:27:20,830 --> 00:27:22,193
even around Christmas.

474
00:27:23,630 --> 00:27:25,633
Nancy started seeing a psychiatrist.

475
00:27:27,470 --> 00:27:29,040
I remember it just seemed to be

476
00:27:29,040 --> 00:27:33,470
a very hard time for everybody,
Anna and Allison too.

477
00:27:33,470 --> 00:27:37,317
- Isn't Daddy coming?

478
00:27:38,314 --> 00:27:40,603
- I'm not sure sweetheart.

479
00:27:42,058 --> 00:27:44,541
- [Allison] I want him to come home.

480
00:27:44,541 --> 00:27:46,736
(Christmas music)

481
00:27:46,736 --> 00:27:49,320
- Well, you remember when Mommy
used to work all the time?

482
00:27:49,320 --> 00:27:51,190
Well now Daddy has to work.

483
00:27:51,190 --> 00:27:52,930
We're taking turns.

484
00:27:52,930 --> 00:27:54,432
- Why did you stop working?

485
00:27:54,432 --> 00:27:57,160
(Christmas music)

486
00:27:57,160 --> 00:28:00,144
- Well, 'cause I wanted to spend more time

487
00:28:00,144 --> 00:28:03,231
with my two little girls, that's why.

488
00:28:03,231 --> 00:28:06,810
(Christmas music)

489
00:28:06,810 --> 00:28:08,231
And how 'bout

490
00:28:08,231 --> 00:28:10,701
♪ Jingle bells, Batman smells ♪

491
00:28:10,701 --> 00:28:13,432
♪ Robin laid an egg ♪

492
00:28:13,432 --> 00:28:16,325
♪ Batman lost a tire ♪

493
00:28:16,325 --> 00:28:19,477
♪ And Joker got away, hey ♪

494
00:28:19,477 --> 00:28:20,480
- [Nancy] Oh, that's not nice.

495
00:28:20,480 --> 00:28:21,980
- [Child] Daddy taught us that one.

496
00:28:21,980 --> 00:28:23,420
- [Nancy] Oh he did, well.

497
00:28:23,420 --> 00:28:24,253
- [Girls] Daddy!

498
00:28:26,260 --> 00:28:27,653
- [Richard] Merry Christmas.

499
00:28:31,016 --> 00:28:33,160
- [Child] Are those presents for now?

500
00:28:33,160 --> 00:28:35,323
- [Richard] Don't you want to
wait 'til Christmas morning?

501
00:28:35,323 --> 00:28:36,338
- [Child] No way!

502
00:28:36,338 --> 00:28:37,673
- [Richard] Okay, but
just one a piece now.

503
00:28:44,085 --> 00:28:45,835
- Home for Christmas?

504
00:28:48,200 --> 00:28:49,450
- Well I can't miss that.

505
00:28:54,161 --> 00:28:56,158
- [Nancy] Well yeah, but you just come

506
00:28:56,158 --> 00:28:59,410
and drop off gifts and then take off.

507
00:28:59,410 --> 00:29:01,020
- [Richard] What am I supposed to do,

508
00:29:01,020 --> 00:29:02,620
pretend like nothing's wrong?

509
00:29:02,620 --> 00:29:03,910
The way your whole family has been

510
00:29:03,910 --> 00:29:05,887
pretending for the last 30 years.

511
00:29:05,887 --> 00:29:07,630
- [Nancy] Why do you keep harping on it,

512
00:29:07,630 --> 00:29:08,930
I'm dealing with it.

513
00:29:08,930 --> 00:29:10,170
- Dealing with it, how?

514
00:29:10,170 --> 00:29:13,160
By quitting your job, by
seeing a shrink all the time?

515
00:29:13,160 --> 00:29:14,517
Look at you, you're unraveling.

516
00:29:14,517 --> 00:29:17,380
- Of course I'm unraveling,
I mean you walk out,

517
00:29:17,380 --> 00:29:18,712
you take up with another woman.

518
00:29:18,712 --> 00:29:20,550
Don't tell me that's a handful.

519
00:29:20,550 --> 00:29:22,800
- I didn't want it to turn out like this.

520
00:29:22,800 --> 00:29:24,590
- I even get bills for her jewelry.

521
00:29:24,590 --> 00:29:26,153
- You think I wanted it
to turn out like this?

522
00:29:26,153 --> 00:29:28,116
- It just all makes me sick.

523
00:29:28,116 --> 00:29:29,273
I mean if you're so all new and Christian,

524
00:29:29,273 --> 00:29:30,510
